video:video.video:title: Cash bouquets and scrap metal gifts rival flowers as coveted tokens of love in Zimbabwe
video:video.video:description: Romance in Zimbabwe is taking strikingly inventive forms, reflecting life in an economy where cash reigns supreme and sustainability gains new social value.

video:video.video:title: Palestinians look to salvage Gaza's history from ruins of Israel's military offensive
video:video.video:description: Today, much of the enclave's heritage sites stand in ruins – like most of Gaza – after being hit by Israeli strikes in a two-year war muffled by an uncertain ceasefire.

video:video.video:title: Mental health patients join Rio carnival street party to break stigma and promote inclusion
video:video.video:description: Patients of a mental health institution joined revellers on the streets of Rio de Janeiro on Thursday for the annual 'Suburban Madness' pre-carnival parade, which promotes mental health inclusion and challenges stigma.

video:video.video:title: Conservationists near New Orleans nearing goal of planting 30,000 trees
video:video.video:description: In wetlands near New Orleans, a coalition of local conservation groups are in the final year of a four-year project to plant 30,000 trees, to better protect the shorelines from storm surges due to extreme weather and prevent further erosion and saltwater intrusion.

video:video.video:title: Goldman Sachs' top lawyer Kathy Ruemmler to resign after emails show close ties to Jeffrey Epstein
video:video.video:description: Goldman Sachs’ top lawyer Kathy Ruemmler is resigning after emails revealed she had a close relationship with Jeffrey Epstein.

video:video.video:title: World Cup buildup strains livelihoods of Mexico City’s sex workers
video:video.video:description: As Mexico City gears up for the 2026 World Cup, construction and new bike lanes are reshaping the streets where Monserrat Fuentes has worked for two decades, cutting her income in half.
